subaward_description: THE CONTRACTOR WILL DEVELOP, OPTIMIZE, AND COMPARE LINEARIZED ENCODING MODELS, FOCUSED ON AUDITORY AND SPEEECH STIMULI.  USE EXISTING HUMAN ECOG DATA (FROM KINGHT LAB) TO COMPARE ENCODING MODEL PREDICTIVE ACCURACY USING SPECIFIC NONLINEAR TRAMSFORMATIONS OF STIMULUS (E.G., SPECTOGRAM, MODULATION, PHONEME, SYLLABLE, SEMANTIC REPRESENTATIONS) AND NEURAL RESPONSE (E.G., TIME-FREQUENCY DECOMPOSITION).  QUNTIFY NEURAL TUNING AND SAMPLING OF THE STIMULUS SPACE OVER THE RECORDED NUERAL POPULATIONS. ASSESS HOW PREDICTIVE ACCURACY AND STIMULUS SPACE SMPLING INCREASES WITH INCREASING NUMBER OF CHANNELS USING INITIAL DISTRIBUTED COMPUTING INPLEMENTATION OF MODEL FITTING PROCEDURES FOR LARG-SCALE RECORDINGS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: THE GOAL OF THE POWER EFFICIENCY REVOLUTION FOR EMBEDDED COMPUTING TECHNOLOGIES (PERFECT) PROGRAM IS TO PROVIDE THE TECHNOLOGIES AND TECHNIQUES TO OVERCOME THE POWER EFFICIENCY BARRIERS THAT CURRENTLY CONSTRAIN EMBEDDED COMPUTING SYSTEMS CAPABILITES AND LIMIT THE POTENTIAL OF FUTURE EMBEDDED SYSTEMS.
prime_award_project_title: ESP: Embedded Scalable Platforms for Terascale Energy-Efficient Computing
prime_award_naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTECHNOLOGY)
subawardee_name: REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, THE
subawardee_business_types: 1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,CONTRACTS AND GRANTS,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION,OTHER NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANIZATION
subaward_description:
THE GOAL OF THE POWER EFFICIENCY REVOLUTION FOR EMBEDDED COMPUTING TECHNOLOGIES (PERFECT) PROGRAM IS TO PROVIDE A POWER EFFICIENCY OF 75 GFLOPS/W FOR EMBEDDED COMPUTING SYSTEMS. THE PERFECT PROGRAM WILL ACHIEVE THIS GOAL BY TAKING A REVOLUTIONARY APPROACH TO PROCESSING POWER EFFICIENCY. THIS APPROACH INCLUDES NEAR THRESHOLD VOLTAGE OPERATION AND MASSIVE HETEROGENEOUS
 PROCESSING CONCURRENCY, COMBINED WITH TECHNIQUES TO EFFECTIVELY UTILIZE THE RESULTING CONCURRENCY AND TOLERATE THE RESULTING INCREASED RATE OF SOFT ERRORS. THE PERFECT PROGRAM WILL LEVERAGE AND INCORPORATE ANTICIPATED INDUSTRY FABRICATION GEOMETRY ADVANCES TO 7 NM. SINCE NO OPERATIONAL HARDWARE IS TO BE BUILT IN THIS PROGRAM, A SIMULATION CAPABILITY WILL BE DEVELOPED TO MEASURE AND DEMONSTRATE PROGRESS. THIS PROGRAM SPECIFICALLY ADDRESSES EMBEDDED SYSTEMS PROCESSING POWER EFFICIENCIES AND PERFORMANCE, AND IS NOT CONCERNED WITH DEVELOPMENTS THAT FOCUS ON EXASCALE PROCESSING ISSUES.
 IN THE FRAMEWORK OF THE PERFECT PROGRAM, THE EMBEDDED SCALABLE PLATFORMS (ESP) TEAM WILL DEVELOP
 A NEW GENERATION OF PLATFORM ARCHITECTURES THAT YIELD OPTIMAL ENERGY-PERFORMANCE OPERATIONS WHILE
 SUPPORTING A DIVERSITY OF EMBEDDED APPLICATION WORKLOADS. THIS GOAL WILL BE ACHIEVED THROUGH A SET OF SCALABLE INNOVATIONS IN CIRCUITS, ARCHITECTURE, SOFTWARE, AND CAD INCLUDING: SCALABLE 3D-STACKED VOLTAGE
 REGULATORS FOR INTEGRATED FINE-GRAIN POWER MANAGEMENT; HIGHLY-RESILIENT NEAR-THRESHOLD-VOLTAGE OPERATION
 THROUGH COMPREHENSIVE RESILIENCY MANAGEMENT; SEAMLESS INTEGRATION OF PROGRAMMABLE CORES AND SPECIALIZED ACCELERATORS INTO A SCALABLE SYSTEM-ON-CHIP (SOC) ARCHITECTURE ORGANIZED IN A TILE-BASED DESIGN; SCALABLE NETWORK-ON-CHIP INFRASTRUCTURE FOR BOTH MESSAGE-PASSING COMMUNICATIONS AND DISTRIBUTED
 POWER CONTROL; STATIC AND DYNAMIC SCHEDULING OF ON-CHIP RESOURCES DRIVEN BY PERFORMANCE PROFILING; AND AN INTEGRATED ENVIRONMENT FOR FULL-SYSTEM SIMULATION AND APPLICATION-DRIVEN OPTIMIZATION. LED BY COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY AND COMPRISING RESEARCHERS FROM PRINCETON UNIVERSITY, UC BERKELEY, AND IBM, THE ESP TEAM WILL DEMONSTRATE THE PROPOSED RESEARCH INNOVATIONS THROUGH THE DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION OF TWO MULTI-CORE SOC PROTOTYPES WHICH WILL BE FABRICATED BY IBM.
 PHASE I. BASIC TECHNOLOGY DEMONSTRATIONS. (18 MONTHS) IN PHASE I, WE WILL FOCUS ON BASIC TECHNOLOGY
 DEMONSTRATIONS AND DEVELOPMENT TO ENABLE THE ESPI PROTOTYPE IN PHASE II.
 TASK 1.1. DEVELOPMENT OF KEY HARDWARE COMPONENTS OF THE ESP PROCESSOR.
 MILESTONE 1.1.1. DEMONSTRATION OF 3D-INTEGRATED SIVRS SUPPORTING AT LEAST 16 POWER DOMAINS WITH AN AVERAGE EFFICIENCY OF AT LEAST 85% AT AN INPUT VOLTAGE OF GREATER THAN 2 V AND AT A MAXIMUM CURRENT OF 10 A PER DOMAIN WITH AN AVERAGE VOLTAGE RIPPLE OF LESS THAN 15 M V AND A RESPONSE TIME OF LESS THAN 5 NS.
 GALLAGHER, SULLIVAN, KNICKERBOCKER, ANDRY (IBM): SHEPARD (COLUMBIA).
 COMPLETION CRITERIA AND DELIVERABLES: FUNCTIONING SIVR HARDWARE.
 APPROACH: ACHIEVING THIS MILESTONE WILL REQUIRE ADDITIONAL OPTIMIZATION OF THE POWER INDUCTOR STRUCTURES AS DESCRIBED IN SECTION D. THE INTERPOSER WILL CONTAIN THE INDUCTORS,CAPACITORS, AND THE POWER TRAIN OF THE BUCK CONVERTER WHILE THE CONTROL CIRCUITRY WILL BE ON THE PROCESSOR LAYER. ALL DESIGN WILL BE
 DONE AT COLUMBIA AND ALL FABRICATION AT IBM.
 MILESTONE 1.1.2. MAPPING OF ARM PROCESSORS TO AN IBM 32-NM (OR 22-NM) SOL CMOS TECHNOLOGY INCLUDING MULTIPHASE LATCH-BASED DESIGN AND LOW-COST TIMING-ERROR MONITORS. SEOK, SHEPARD (COLUMBIA).
 COMPLETION CRITERIA AND DELIVERABLES: A WORKING GATE/TRANSISTOR-LEVEL LOW POWER HIGH-PERFORMANCE ARM PROCESSOR ENABLING RESILIENT NTV OPERATIONS WITH 5% MARGIN IN CYCLE TIME OVER 10CAVRANDOM PVT VARIATIONS, IMPLEMENTED IN AN IBM 32-NM (OR 22-NM) SOL CMOS TECHNOLOGY.
 APPROACH: WE WILL EXPLORE THE OPTIMAL PLACEMENT OF LATCHES AND TIMING ERROR MONITORS. WE ALSO PLAN TO CO-DESIGN CLOCK DISTRIBUTION NETWORKS AND LOCAL NON-OVERLAPPING CLOCK GENERATORS TO ELIMINATE HOLD
 TIME VIOLATIONS.

 THROUGH COMPREHENSIVE RESILIENCY MANAGEMENT; SEAMLESS INTEGRATION OF PROGRAMMABLE CORES AND SPECIALIZED ACCELERATORS INTO A SCALABLE SYSTEM-ON-CHIP (SOC) ARCHITECTURE ORGANIZED IN A TILE-BASED DESIGN; SCALABLE NETWORK-ON-CHIP INFRASTRUCTURE FOR BOTH MESSAGE-PASSING COMMUNICATIONS AND DISTRIBUTED
 POWER CONTROL; STATIC AND DYNAMIC SCHEDULING OF ON-CHIP RESOURCES DRIVEN BY PERFORMANCE PROFILING; AND AN INTEGRATED ENVIRONMENT FOR FULL-SYSTEM SIMULATION AND APPLICATION-DRIVEN OPTIMIZATION. LED BY COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY AND COMPRISING RESEARCHERS FROM PRINCETON UNIVERSITY, UC BERKELEY, AND IBM, THE ESP TEAM WILL DEMONSTRATE THE PROPOSED RESEARCH INNOVATIONS THROUGH THE DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION OF TWO MULTI-CORE SOC PROTOTYPES WHICH WILL BE FABRICATED BY IBM.
 PHASE I. BASIC TECHNOLOGY DEMONSTRATIONS. (18 MONTHS) IN PHASE I, WE WILL FOCUS ON BASIC TECHNOLOGY
 DEMONSTRATIONS AND DEVELOPMENT TO ENABLE THE ESPI PROTOTYPE IN PHASE II.
 TASK 1.1. DEVELOPMENT OF KEY HARDWARE COMPONENTS OF THE ESP PROCESSOR.
 MILESTONE 1.1.1. DEMONSTRATION OF 3D-INTEGRATED SIVRS SUPPORTING AT LEAST 16 POWER DOMAINS WITH AN AVERAGE EFFICIENCY OF AT LEAST 85% AT AN INPUT VOLTAGE OF GREATER THAN 2 V AND AT A MAXIMUM CURRENT OF 10 A PER DOMAIN WITH AN AVERAGE VOLTAGE RIPPLE OF LESS THAN 15 M V AND A RESPONSE TIME OF LESS THAN 5 NS.
 GALLAGHER, SULLIVAN, KNICKERBOCKER, ANDRY (IBM): SHEPARD (COLUMBIA).
 COMPLETION CRITERIA AND DELIVERABLES: FUNCTIONING SIVR HARDWARE.
 APPROACH: ACHIEVING THIS MILESTONE WILL REQUIRE ADDITIONAL OPTIMIZATION OF THE POWER INDUCTOR STRUCTURES AS DESCRIBED IN SECTION D. THE INTERPOSER WILL CONTAIN THE INDUCTORS,CAPACITORS, AND THE POWER TRAIN OF THE BUCK CONVERTER WHILE THE CONTROL CIRCUITRY WILL BE ON THE PROCESSOR LAYER. ALL DESIGN WILL BE
 DONE AT COLUMBIA AND ALL FABRICATION AT IBM.
 MILESTONE 1.1.2. MAPPING OF ARM PROCESSORS TO AN IBM 32-NM (OR 22-NM) SOL CMOS TECHNOLOGY INCLUDING MULTIPHASE LATCH-BASED DESIGN AND LOW-COST TIMING-ERROR MONITORS. SEOK, SHEPARD (COLUMBIA).
 COMPLETION CRITERIA AND DELIVERABLES: A WORKING GATE/TRANSISTOR-LEVEL LOW POWER HIGH-PERFORMANCE ARM PROCESSOR ENABLING RESILIENT NTV OPERATIONS WITH 5% MARGIN IN CYCLE TIME OVER 10CAVRANDOM PVT VARIATIONS, IMPLEMENTED IN AN IBM 32-NM (OR 22-NM) SOL CMOS TECHNOLOGY.
 APPROACH: WE WILL EXPLORE THE OPTIMAL PLACEMENT OF LATCHES AND TIMING ERROR MONITORS. WE ALSO PLAN TO CO-DESIGN CLOCK DISTRIBUTION NETWORKS AND LOCAL NON-OVERLAPPING CLOCK GENERATORS TO ELIMINATE HOLD
 TIME VIOLATIONS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: THE GOAL OF THIS PROGRAM IS TO DEVELOP A COMPLETE LIBRARY OF LOGIC ELEMENTS/BUILDING BLOCKS THAT PERFORM LOGICAL FUNCTIONS BY EXPLOITING NEW COMPUTATIONAL STATE VARIABLES SUCH AS MAGNETIZATION AND WHICH CAN RETAIN THEIR STATE WHEN POWER IS REMOVED.

 2150 SHATTUCK AVENUE ROOM 313
subawardee_business_types: CONTRACTS AND GRANTS,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION,OTHER NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANIZATION
subaward_description: THE UC-BERKELEY TEAM WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR TWO OF THE MAJOR TASKS WITHIN THE PROJECT (MC AND EAC), AND WILL ALSO BE RESPONSIBLE FOR PARTICULAR CONTRIBUTIONS TO ONE OF THE OTHER MAJOR TASKS WITHIN THE PROJECT (DS): TASK 1 IS MULTIFERROIC CLOCKING (MC). THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS TASK IS TO DEMONSTRATE CLOCKING OF NANOMAGNETIC LOGIC USING EXCHANGE COUPLING TO THE MULTIFERROIC MATERIAL BISMUTH FERRITE (BFO). THE APPROACH IS TO FABRICATE FERROMAGNETIC NANOMAGNETS ON TOP OF A HIGH QUALITY BFO LAYER AND INTEGRATE VOLTAGE CONTACTS IN ORDER TO APPLY THE ELECTRIC FIELD TO THE BFO. NANOMAGNETS WILL BE PATTERNED USING ION MILLING LITHOGRAPHY. MC WILL FIRST BE DEMONSTRATED IN PHASE 1 FOR A SIMPLE LINEAR CHAIN OF NANOMAGNETS. IF SUCCESSFUL, MC WILL BE INTEGRATED INTO THE FULL NANOMAGNETIC LOGIC CIRCUIT IN PHASE 2. THE TEAM MEMBERS RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS TASK ARE R. RAMESH, S. SALAHUDDIN, AND J. BOKOR. TASK 2 IS ERROR ANALYSIS AND CONTROL (EAC). THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS TASK IS TO CHARACTERIZE AND ENSURE RELIABILITY OF OPERATION OF NANOMAGNETIC LOGIC CIRCUITS. THE APPROACH IS TO DEVELOP METHODS FOR RAPID CHARACTERIZATION OF ERRORS IN NANOMAGNETIC CHAINS AND LOGIC GATES IN ORDER TO BUILD UP STATISTICS. INCORPORATION OF MAGNETOCRYSTALLINE BIAXIAL ANISOTROPY INTO THE FERROMAGNETIC ISLANDS IS AN APPROACH TO ACHIEVE ROBUST OPERATION AND WILL BE EVALUATED FOR IMPROVEMENT OF CIRCUIT RELIABILITY. PHOTO-EMISSION ELECTRON MICROSCOPY (PEEM) IS A METHOD THAT CAN BE USED TO FORM MAGNETIC IMAGES OF LARGE ARRAYS OF CHAINS AND GATES AND WILL BE USED TO GATHER STATISTICS ON ERROR RATES. THE TEAM MEMBER RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS TASK IS J. BOKOR. TASK 3 IS DESIGN SPACE EXPLORATION (DS). WHILE ALL OF THE SUB-COMPONENTS NEEDED FOR A 2-BIT ADDER HAVE BEEN EXPERIMENTALLY DEMONSTRATED, THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS TASK IS TO DETERMINE WHAT NML DEVICE/CIRCUIT FEATURES WILL ALLOW AN INTEGRATED ENSEMBLE OF MAGNETS TO PERFORM A 2-BIT ADDITION WITH LEAST AMOUNT OF ENERGY FROM THE CLOCK. THE APPROACH TO THIS PROBLEM WILL BE A SIMULATION-BASED DESIGN SPACE EXPLORATION. DESIGNS INCORPORATING MULTIFERROIC CLOCKING AND/OR BIAXIAL ANISOTROPY WILL BE EXPLORED. THE TEAM MEMBER RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS TASK IS J. BOKOR.

 THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, BERKELEY, PROPOSES TO PERFORM THE FOLLOWING TASKS IN SUPPORT OF THE MODEL-BASED AMPHIBIOUS RACING CHALLENGE (MBARC). THE BASE PERIOD FOR THIS EFFORT IS 12 MONTHS; ALONG WITH AN OPTION PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE OF 12 MONTHS.
 TASK 1. META DESIGN FORMULATION (YEAR 1)
 THE UCB TEAM WILL DEVELOP CURRICULA TO INTRODUCE THE METHODS, TOOLS AND TECHNIQUES DEVELOPED FOR THE META PROGRAM. THE LECTURE MATERIALS WILL BE MADE AVAILABLE THROUGH OPEN SOURCE (E.G. MIT OPEN COURSE WARE HTTP://OCW.MIT.EDU).THESE WILL INCLUDE MODEL-BASED DESIGN, INTEGRATION OF EXISTING OPEN SOURCE SOFTWARE FOR EQUATION FORMULATION AND EFFICIENT SIMULATION AND OPTIMIZATION.
 DELIVERABLE: REPORT ON MODEL-BASE DESIGN FORMULATION, 4 MONTHS FROM ATP.
 TASK 2. META CLASS (YEAR 1)
 THE UCB TEAM WILL IMPLEMENT THE PREVIOUSLY MENTIONED MODEL-BASED DESIGN CLASS TO SUPPORT THE ACADEMIC COMPETITIVE TEAM THAT WILL PARTICIPATE IN THE MBARC COMPETITION.
 DELIVERABLE: REPORT ON DESIGN CLASS EXECUTION, 6 MONTHS FROM ATP.
 TASK 3. MBARC COMPETITION (YEAR 1)
 THE UCB TEAM WILL PARTICIPATE IN THE MBARC COMPETITION, WHICH IS TENTATIVELY PLANNED TO BE ORGANIZED AT CAMP PENDLETON, CA IN JANUARY 2013 OR AN ALTERNATIVE UNITED STATES LOCATION.
 DELIVERABLE: BASE PERIOD FINAL REPORT, 12 MONTHS FROM ATP.
 TASK 4. (OPTION) META CLASS (YEAR 2)
 THE UCB TEAM WILL CONTINUE TO EXECUTE IMPROVED VERSION OF THE PREVIOUSLY MENTIONED CLASS TO SUPPORT THE COMPETITIVE ACADEMIC TEAM THAT WILL PARTICIPATE IN THE MBARC COMPETITION.
 DELIVERABLE: REPORT ON DESIGN CLASS REFINEMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION, 16 MONTHS FROM ATP.
 PERIODIC DELIVERABLES
 IN ADDITION TO THE DELIVERABLE IDENTIFIED WITH THE TASKS, UCB WILL PROVIDE THE FOLLOWING DELIVERABLES ON A PERIODIC BASIS AS IDENTIFIED BELOW: TELECON MINUTES AND PRESENTATION MATERIAL FOR TELECONFERENCES (BI-WEEKLY FROM AUTHORIZATION TO PROCEED (ATP))
 TECHNICAL STATUS REPORT DETAILING TECHNICAL PROGRESS, PLANS, RISK, AND CHALLENGES/ISSUES ENCOUNTERED WITH MITIGATION PLANS AS APPROPRIATE (MONTHLY FROM ATP)
 FINANCIAL STATUS REPORTING, INCLUDING LABOR, TRAVEL, AND ODC EXPENDITURE FOR THE PREVIOUS MONTH AND PLANS FOR THE CURRENT MONTH. INCLUDE HOURS CHARGED TO THE CONTRACT BY NAMED INDIVIDUAL (MONTHLY FROM ATP)

subaward_description: THE PROPOSED STUDY IS COLLABORATIVE PROGRAM COVERING THE CHEMICAL MODELING, STATISTICAL MODELING OF THE PARTICLE SIZE DISTRIBUTION AND PARTICLE DYNAMICS, AND THE INTERACTIONS OF SOOT FORMATION AND OXIDATION WITH TURBULENCE.  THE OBJECTIVE IS TO DEVEL OP DETAILED CHEMICAL-KINETICS BASED, INTEGRATED SOOT MODELS FOR LARGE-EDDY SIMULATION (LES) OF GAS TURBINE ENGINE COMBUSTION.  THE PROPOSAL IS A CONTINUATION OF THE ONGOING COLLABORATIVE WORK UNDER THE SAME SPONSOR.  THE SPECIFIC OBJECTIVES TO BE COV ERED AT UC BERKELEY ARE IN THE AREA OF CHEMICAL MODELING. THE ACCOMPLISHMENTS OF THE UC BERKELEY TEAM FROM THE PRIOR FUNDING ARE: COMPLETED MD SIMULATIONS OF COLLISIONS OF OXYGENATED PAHS, ESTABLISHED THERMODYNAMIC STABILITY OF KEY OXYGENATED RADICAL  INTERMEDIATES, AND INITIATED INVESTIGATION OF REACTION KINETICS OF SOOT OXIDATION.  THE PROPOSED NEW TASKS TO BE PERFORMED ARE AS FOLLOWS. 1)COMPLETION OF SURFACE OXIDATION MODEL. THE THEORETICAL STUDY OF THE SOOT OXIDATION KINETICS WILL BE COMPLET ED AND A DETAILED RACTION MODEL CREATED DESCRIBING OXIDATIVE DESTRUCTION OF SOOT.  THE INITIAL MODEL WILL ACCOUNT FOR THE PRIMARY OXIDATIVE AGENTS, O2 AND OH.  ADDITIONAL SPECIES WILL BE ADDED (E.G., H2O, HO2, CO2, ETC) DURING THE COURSE OF THE PROJE CT. THIS WILL EXTEND MODEL APPLICABILITY TO A BROADER VARIETY OF FUELS AND COMBUSTION ENVIRONMENTS.  ATTENTION WILL BE GIVEN TO EMERGING ALTERNATIVE FUELS AND NOVEL ENERGY-GENERATING TECHNOLOGIES. 2)GENERATION OF THE COMBINED MODEL.  THE DETAILED RE ACTION MODEL OF SOOT OXIDATION, DEVELOPED IN PART 1 ABOVE, WILL BE COMBINED WITH A DETAILED REACTION MODEL OF SOOT PARTICLE GROWTH.  THE INITIAL MODEL WILL BE TAKEN FROM THE ONGOING WORK OF FRENKLACH UNDER THE DOE-BES PROGRAM. THE MODEL WILL BE CONTI NUOUSLY UPDATED BASED ON THE RESULTS OF THE DOE-BES STUDY AND TO ACCOUNT FOR ADDITIONAL GROWTH SPECIES REQUIRED FOR APPLICATION TO ALTERNATIVE FUELS AND NOVEL ENERGY-GENERATING TECHNOLOGIES, AS DESCRIBED ABOVE. 3)DEVELOPMENT OF A SIMPLE KINETIC MODE L.  A SIMPLE KINETIC MODEL WILL BE DEVELOPED TO REPRESENT ACCURATELY THE DYNAMICS OF THE COMBINED DETAILED SURFACE MODEL BUT IN A COMPUTATIONALLY ECONOMIC MANNER FOR INCLUSION INTO THE LES FLAME MODELS.  THE DEVELOPMENT WILL INCLUDE PERFORMING A SERI ES OF DETAILED MONTE CARLO SIMULATIONS AT THE CONDITIONS CAPTURING THE FLAME ENVIRONMENTS AND PARAMETERIZING THE RESULTS INTO A SIMPLE, ONE-OR TWO-STEP KINETIC MODEL.  THE KINETIC PARAMETERIZATION WILL BE BASED ON TWO PRINCIPAL ELEMENTS: PARAMETERIZ ING AND FITTING THE NUCLEATION RATE AND PARAMETERIZING AND FITTING THE SURFACE GROWTH RATE.  FOR THE NUCLEATION RATE WE WILL START BY EMPLOYING THE PYRENE-COLLISION MODEL WITH AN ADJUSTABLE PARAMETER, CALIBRATED IN A CONSISTENT AND SYSTEMATIC MANNER,  EXPLORING ITS POSSIBLE DEPENDENCIES ON ENVIRONMENTAL VARIABLES (TEMPERATURE AND PRESSURE) AND THE INITIAL FUEL.  FOR THE SURFACE GROWTH/OXIDATION RATE WE WILL START WITH THE PAST PARAMETERIZATION SCHEME AND EXPAND IT TO ACCOUNT FOR THE COMPLEXITY OF  THE SURFACE PROCESSES DISCOVERED SINCE THEN. 4)VALIDATION OF THE CHEMICAL MODEL.  THE VALIDATION WILL BE PERFORMED IN TWO STEPS.  FIRST, WE WILL VALIDATE THE COMPLETE DETAILED REACTION MODEL, COMPOSED OF THE MAIN-COMBUSTION REACTIONS, SOOT SURFACE GROWTH MECHANISM, AND SOOT SURFACE OXIDATION REACTIONS.  THIS PART OF THE VALIDATION WILL BE BASED ON LABORATORY EXPERIMENTS AND WILL BE ACCOMPLISHED UTILIZING THE PRIME INFRASTRUCTURE.  IN THE SECOND STEP OF THE VALIDATION WE WILL TEST THE SIMPLE, P ARAMETERIZED KINETIC MODEL AGAINST THE DETAILED MODEL.

THE PROPOSED STUDY IS A COLLABORATIVE PROGRAM COVERING THE CHEMICAL MODELING, STATISTICAL MODELING OF THE PARTICLE SIZE DISTRIBUTION AND PARTICLE DYNAMICS, AND THE INTERACTIONS OF SOOT FORMATION AND OXIDATION WITH TURBULENCE. THE OBJECTIVE IS TO DEVELOP DETAILED CHEMICAL-KINETICS BASED, INTEGRATED SOOT MODELS FOR LARGE-EDDY SIMULATION (LES) OF GAS TURBINE ENGINE COMBUSTION. THE PROPOSAL IS A CONTINUATION OF THE ONGOING COLLABORATIVE WORK UNDER THE SAME SPONSOR. THE SPECIFIC OBJECTIVES TO BE COVERED AT UC BERKELEY ARE IN THE AREA OF CHEMICAL MODELING.
 THE ACCOMPLISHMENTS OF THE UC BERKELEY TEAM FROM THE PRIOR FUNDING ARE: COMPLETED MD SIMULATIONS OF COLLISIONS OF OXYGENATED PAHS, ESTABLISHED THERMODYNAMIC STABILITY OF KEY OXYGENATED RADICAL INTERMEDIATES, AND INITIATED INVESTIGATION OF REACTION KINETICS OF SOOT OXIDATION. THE PROPOSED NEW TASKS TO BE PERFORMED ARE AS FOLLOWS.
 1) COMPLETION OF SURFACE OXIDATION MODEL. THE THEORETICAL STUDY OF THE SOOT OXIDATION KINETICS WILL BE COMPLETED AND A DETAILED REACTION MODEL CREATED DESCRIBING OXIDATIVE DESTRUCTION OF SOOT. THE INITIAL MODEL WILL ACCOUNT FOR THE PRIMARY OXIDATIVE AGENTS, 02 AND OH. ADDITIONAL SPECIES WILL BE ADDED (E.G." H20, H02, C02, ETC) DURING THE COURSE OF THE PROJECT. THIS WILL EXTEND MODEL APPLICABILITY TO A BROADER VARIETY OF FUELS AND COMBUSTION ENVIRONMENTS. ATTENTION WILL BE GIVEN TO EMERGING ALTERNATIVE FUELS AND NOVEL ENERGY-GENERATING TECHNOLOGIES,
 2)GENERATION OF THE COMBINED MODEL. THE DETAILED REACTION MODEL OF SOOT OXIDATION, DEVELOPED IN PART 1 ABOVE, WILL BE COMBINED WITH THE DETAILED REACTION MODEL OF SOOT PARTICLE GROWTH. THE INITIAL MODEL WILL BE TAKEN FROM THE ONGOING WORK OF FRENKLACH UNDER THE DOE-BES PROGRAM. THE MODEL WILL BE CONTINUOUSLY UPDATED BASED ON THE RESULTS OF THE DOE-BES STUDY AND TO ACCOUNT FOR ADDITIONAL GROWTH SPECIES REQUIRED FOR APPLICATION TO ALTERNATIVE FUELS AND NOVEL ENERGY-GENERATING TECHNOLOGIES, AS DESCRIBED ABOVE.
 3) DEVELOPMENT OF A SIMPLE KINETIC MODEL. A SIMPLE KINETIC MODEL WILL BE DEVELOPED TO REPRESENT ACCURATELY THE DYNAMICS OF THE COMBINED DETAILED SURFACE MODEL BUT IN A COMPUTATIONALLY ECONOMIC MANNER FOR THE INCLUSION INTO THE LES FLAME MODELS. THE DEVELOPMENT WILL INCLUDE PERFORMING A SERIES OF DETAILED MONTE CARLO SIMULATIONS AT THE CONDITIONS CAPTURING THE FLAME ENVIRONMENTS AND PARAMETERIZING THE RESULTS INTO A SIMPLE, ONE- OR TW-STEP KINETIC MODEL. THE KINETIC PARAMETERIZATION WILL BE BASED ON TWO PRINCIPAL ELEMENTS: PARAMETERIZING AND FITTING THE NUCLEATION RATE AND PARAMETERIZING AND FITTING THE SURFACE GROWTH RATE. FOR THE NUCLEATION RATE WE WILL START BY EMPLOYING THE PYRENE-COLLISION MODEL WITH AN ADJUSTABLE PARAMETER, CALIBRATED IN A CONSISTENT AND SYSTEMATIC MANNER, EXPLORING ITS POSSIBLE DEPENDENCIES ON ENVIRONMENTAL VARIABLES (TEMPERATURE AND PRESSURE) AND THE INITIAL FUEL. FOR THE SURFACE GROWTH/OXIDATION RATE WE WILL START WITH THE PAST PARAMETERIZATION SCHEME AND EXPAND IT TO ACCOUNT FOR THE COMPLEXITY OF THE SURFACE GROWTH/OXIDATION RATE WE WILL START WITH THE PAST PARAMETERIZATION SCHEME AND EXPAND IT TO ACCOUNT FOR THE COMPLEXITY OF THE SURFACE PROCESSES DISCOVERED SINCE THEN.
 4) VALIDATION OF THE CHEMICAL MODEL. THE VALIDATION WILL BE PERFORMED IN TWO STEPS, FIRST WE WILL VALIDATE THE COMPLETE DETAILED REACTION MODEL, COMPOSED OF THE MAIN-COMBUSTION REACTIONS, SOOT SURFACE GROWTH MECHANISM, AND SOOT SURFACE OXIDATION REACTIONS. THIS PART OF THE VALIDATION WILL BE BASED ON LABORATORY EXPERIMENTS AND WILL BE ACCOMPLISHED UTILIZING THE PRIME INFRASTRUCTURE. IN THE SECOND STEP OF THE VALIDATION WE WILL TEST THE SIMPLE, PARAMETERIZED KINETIC MODEL AGAINSTED THE DETAILED MODEL.

subawardee_business_types: 1862 LAND GRANT COLLEGE,EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION,OTHER NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANIZATION
subaward_description: A NOVEL APPROACH TO EFFORTLESSLY EXTEND THE POWERING AND COMMUNICATION RANGE FROM 1 MM TO 1 CM, 10 CM, AND 1 M, WHILE FULLY HARNESSING THE BUILD-IN TRUST AND ANTI-TAMPERING FUNCTIONS OF THE LOW COST SHIELD DIELETS. THE ENGINEERED "RANGE EXTENDER'' CARRY A SHIELD DIELET AND EXTENDS ITS POWERING AND COMMUNICATION RANGE WITHOUT IMPACTING ITS CORE FUNCTION. THE EXTENDERS HAVE VERY LOW COST IN MANUFACTURING AND ASSEMBLY WITH SHIELD DIELETS, VERY HIGH TOLERANCE TO MISALIGNMENT, WHICH GREATLY SIMPLIFY THE AUTHENTICATION PROCESS BY END-USERS. TO ACHIEVE 1CM, THE CORE IDEAS INCLUDE A 3 AND 4 COIL SYSTEM WITH THE 3RD AND 4TH COILS ACTING AS THE EXTENDER ON A LOW-COST PLATFORM (E.G. FLEXIBLE SUBSTRATES). FOR 10 CM RANGE, WE PROPOSE A DISTRIBUTED ARRAY AS READER TO COUPLE TO A 3 OR 4 COIL SYSTEM FOR MORE RANGE EXTENSION. FOR A METER, WE PROPOSE SOUND WAVES EMITTED BY SPEAKERS TO POWER AND COMMUNICATION. THE SHIELD TECHNOLOGY VEHICLES (STV) DEVELOPED IN PHASE I AND PHASE I EXTENSION WILL BE USED FOR TESTING RANGE EXTENDERS.

subaward_description:
UC BERKELEY WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR PERFORMING THE ACTIVITIES DESCRIBED IN TASK 3 AND WITH PROVIDING ASSISTANCE WITH ACTIVITIES DESCRIBED IN TASK 4. UC BERKELEY WILL ALSO CONTRIBUTE TO THE
 EFFORTS TO DISSEMINATE THE RESULTS OF THE RESEARCH BY PUBLISHING PAPERS IN PEER-REVIEWED JOURNALS AND PRESENTING FINDINGS AT SCIENTIFIC CONFERENCES.
 WORK ON BOTH TASKS WILL BE PERFORMED BY LISA ALVAREZ-COHEN S RESEARCH GROUP.
 RESEARCH TO BE CONDUCTED AS PART OF TASK 3 WILL INVOLVE MICROCOSM STUDIES PERFORMED WITH ENRICHMENT CULTURES DEVELOPED AND GROWN IN THE ALVAREZ-COHEN LABORATORY FROM SAMPLES COLLECTED BY OTHERS AS PART OF TASK 1. MICROBIAL ENRICHMENTS WILL BE GROWN UNDER A VARIETY OF CONDITIONS IN ORDER TO ASSESS PFAS BIOTRANSFORMATION POTENTIAL WITHIN A RANGE OF GEOCHEMICAL CONDITIONS. SUBSEQUENTLY, MICROCOSM STUDIES WILL ALSO BE PERFORMED TO ANALYZE TRANSFORMATION KINETICS AND POTENTIAL PRODUCTS GENERATED BY THE ENRICHMENTS. PFAS IN SAMPLES WILL BE ANALYZED
 IN COLLABORATION WITH THE HIGGINS  AND FIELDS  LABS IN COLORADO AND OREGON, RESPECTIVELY.
 SUBSEQUENTLY, MICROCOSMS WILL BE CONSTRUCTED TO ELUCIDATE THE EFFECTS OF AROMATIC HYDROCARBONS(REPRESENTATIVE COMPOUNDS OF BENZENE,TOLUENE, ETHYLBENZENE AND XYLENES)ON PFAS
 TRANSFORMATIONS. FINALLY, MICROCOSM STUDIES WILL BE PERFORMED TO ASSESS THE EFFECTS OF CHLORINATED SOLVENTS ON PFAS DEGRADATION AND THE EFFECTS OF PFAS ON CHLORINATED SOLVENT DEGRADATION. FOR CULTURES OBSERVED TO BE ACTIVE IN PFAS DEGRADATION, CHARACTERIZATION USING
 MOLECULAR TOOLS WILL BE PERFORMED TO ATTEMPT TO IDENTIFY THE ACTIVE ORGANISMS.
 RESEARCH TO BE CONDUCTED AS PART OF TASK 4 WILL INVOLVE PERFORMING MICROCOSM STUDIES AIMED AT UNDERSTANDING REMEDIAL EFFECTS OF REDUCTIVE DECHLORINATION ON PFAS MIGRATION AS WELL AS THE BIOSPARGING EFFECTS OF ADDING OXYGEN FOR BTEX REMEDIATION. FOR REMEDIATION SYSTEMS OBSERVED TO BE ACTIVE IN PFAS DEGRADATION, CHARACTERIZATION USING MOLECULAR TOOLS WILL BE PERFORMED TO
 ATTEMPT TO IDENTIFY THE ACTIVE ORGANISMS.
 THIS IS A FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PROJECT THAT IS NOT EXPECTED TO PRODUCE ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS. SHOULD ANY DEVELOPMENTAL ITEMS RESULT FROM THIS WORK THEY WILL HAVE BOTH CIVILIAN AND
 MILITARY APPLICATIONS.

subaward_description:
THE EBRC WILL FACILITATE THE PROCESS TO DEVELOP A ROADMAP FOR SYNTHETIC
 BIOLOGY RESEARCH IN THE DOD FOLLOWING THE ARAP SBME PROGRAM. THE PROCESS WILL BE EXECUTED
 WITH A TEAM OF 15-18 CURRENT SBME PERFORMERS (GROUP LEADER LEVEL) AND SUPPLEMENTED BY
 REVIEW AND INPUT FROM A COHORT OF 4-6 EBRC MEMBERS FROM ACADEMIA AND INDUSTRY. THE KEY
 DELIVERABLES WILL INCLUDE A 2-4 PAGE SNAPSHOT GEARED TO SENIOR LEADERS IN THE DOD AND A DETAILED
 VERSION GEARED TOWARD PERFORMERS AND TECHNICAL EXPERTS.

prime_award_base_transaction_description: THE DAPRA SHORT-RANGE INDEPENDENT MICROROBOTIC PLATFORMS (SHRIMP)  PROGRAM WILL DEVELOP AND DEMONSTRATE, THROUGH A SERIES OF OLYMPIC-THEMED COMPETITIONS, MULTI-FUNCTIONAL MM-TO-CM SCALE ROBOTIC PLATFORMS WITH A FOCUS ON UNTETHERED MOBILITY, MANEUVERABILITY, AND DEXTERITY. TO ACHIEVE THIS GOAL, SHRIMP WILL ALSO PROVIDE FOUNDATIONAL RESEARCH IN THE AREA OF MICRO-ACTUATOR MATERIALS AND ENERGY EFFICIENT POWER SYSTEMS FOR EXTREMELY SWAP-CONSTRAINED MICROROBOTIC SYSTEMS. IT IS EXPECTED THAT SUCH ADVANCES WILL BE ENABLING FOR APPLICATIONS INCLUDING SEARCH AND RESCUE, DISASTER RELIEF, HAZARDOUS ENVIRONMENT INSPECTION, IN-FLIGHT CONTROL OF AERODYNAMIC PLATFORMS, STEERABLE OPTICS, AND PROSTHETICS.
